description.narrative: The Swedish Patent and Registration Office (PRV) proposal is for a renewed capacity development program in Intellectual Property (IP) with a focus on Least Developed Countries (LDC). This new program is based on the three previous International Training Programmes (ITP) PRV conducted for more than 10 years and on the results from the 2014 external evaluation of these programs. Additionally, the program will also cover use of IP in the area of Genetic Resources. There are two main arguments for supporting a capacity development program in Intellectual Property in Least Developed Countries (LDC). First, many LDCs lack knowledge of how Intellectual Property (IP) can be used to protect and stimulate the creative arts, innovation, industry and trade and of how IP systems can be developed and used for a country's economic development. Studies have shown that the use of copyright protection alone can contribute to a country's GDP by as much as 5 to 7% (in some developed countries this is much higher, for example 11% for the USA). Add to this the more advanced IP systems in patenting and industrial property and that contribution to GDP jumps to 30 - 40%.The second argument involves the compliance of these countries to the World Trade Organisation (WTO). TRIPS forms part of the WTO system of agreements governing international trade and must be adhered to if a country is to maintain membership in WTO. Least Developed Countries have been given an extended grace period, until 2021, to be able to fulfil the TRIPS requirements. The World Intellectual Property Organisation (WIPO) is working together with the Swedish Patent and Registration Office (PRV) to implement sufficient training for LDCs to be able to develop their IP systems, conform to TRIPS and thereby qualify for continued WTO membership. The planned outcome is that there will be a sufficient human capacity to accomplish the objective of each country developing an IP system, thereby adhering to TRIPS. The Swedish Patent and Registrating Office (PRV) has been running three International Training Programs (ITP) in IP for over 10 years; these programs have addressed the capacity needs of both low and middle countries including LDCs. It is now proposed to prioritise those LDCs identified with the most urgent needs and with the highest potential for economic growth from the introduction of an IP system. The aim of this is to concentrate on obtaining a critical mass of trained people in these LDCs. The participants would come from public institutions, private sector, civil society and academia and would have a mandate to develop the country's IP system. PRV is assisted in the recruitment of key participants by WIPO, the UN organisation responsible for international coordinating efforts in the area of IP. A further development of this proposed program is greater cooperation between PRV and other partners, both in Sweden, EU, and in proposed countries. One example of this is that PRV has been approached by the East African Community (EAC) to assist in establishing regional training programs in Intellectual Property in Arusha, Tanzania. The International Training Programs have proven to be very effective, but they are relatively costly and limited due to available participants who can be accommodated and who are not always able to leave their work for the entire length of a training progrm or at the particular time programs are being offered. Parallel to the traditional ITP programs which are planned to be implemented as previously, it is proposed that some training activities take place locally. Further development of this initiative will only unfold depending on the partners own capacity to take on more of the capacity development in their own countries and/or regions. As such, it is part of this program proposal to further investigate this possibility with several different partners.

Under de senaste tio åren har Patent och Registreringsverket (PRV) genomfört tre International Training Program (ITP) inom immateriellarätt (IP). Den utvärdering av samtliga program som genomfördes under 2014 visar att programmen uppnått förväntade resultat i medverkande länder men också att kapacitetsutveckling inom IP-system fortfarande särskilt behövs för de minst utvecklade länderna (MUL). PRV föreslår nu att koncentrera ett nytt kapacitetsutvecklingsprogram till utvalda MUL där det finns stor potential för goda utvecklingsresultat om välfungerande IP-system kan introduceras och genomföras på landnivå.
PRV har som vision "att minska fattigdomen genom att öka den ekonomiska tillväxten genom att ge utvecklingsländerna en riktig förståelse av, och möjliggöra en informerad och rationell användning av immaterialrättssystemet". IP-system är en förutsättning för hållbar ekonomisk utveckling i samtlliga länder inklusive MUL, eftersom IP-system är värdeskapande genom att stimulera innovation, användning av patent (uppfinningar) och utveckling av den sk kreativa industrin tack vare upphovsrättsligt och varumärkeskydd (branding). Studier genomförda av World International Property Organisation (WIPO) visar att fungerande IP-system kan bidra till ett lands ekonomi med så mycket som 30 - 40% av BNP (varav 5-10 % kan hänföras till upphovsrättigheter).
Dessutom, om MUL ska klara alla krav för fullvärdigt medlemskap i Världshandelsorganisationen (WTO), måste de också uppfylla TRIPS-avtalets handelsrelaterade aspekter av immaterialrätt. Den föreslagna kapacitetsutvecklingsinsatsen för MUL skulle bidra till ländernas uppbyggnad av IP-system som följer TRIPS avtalet och leder till fullvärdigt medlemsskap och del av WTO:s fördelaktiga handelsregler.
Sidas bedömning är att PRV med sitt myndighetsuppdrag har en unik ställning som "bärare" av Sveriges IP-system. Det grundläggande syftet med programmet är att bygga upp MULs myndigheters kapacitet i hantering av immaterialrätt för hela samhällets nytta. Denna roll sammanslagen med PRV:s långa och gedigna erfarenhet och kapacitet att genomföra utbildningar, deras roll som samordnare för de olika aktörerna inom immaterialrätt samt deras breda kontaktnät gör dem till en särskilt strategisk genomförare av IP-systemutbildning. De metoder som tidigare har används har visat sig ha mycket bra möjligheter att nå hållbara resultat i fråga om institutionell förändring, inklusive utveckling av IP-system som ger bättre service till alla medborgare och genererar sysselsättning och nationell ekonomisk tillväxt. Som sådan, passar denna insats väl in i flera av Sidas bilaterala och regionala strategier liksom i resultatstrategin för kapacitetsutveckling och utbyten.

Övergripande mål: Ett lands IP-system utvecklas eller förstärks genom ny utformning av policy, förordningar och/eller lagstiftning, liksom genom stärkt implementering av dessa. Denna utveckling kan bidra till att deltagande länder kan ansluta sig till TRIPS och därmed öka möjligheterna till fullvärdigt medlemskap i WTO.
Outcomenivå: 1. Deltagare hat stärkt kaacitet att arbeta med immaterialrätt och att genomföra sina identifierade förändringsprojekt. 2. Deltagarnas hemorganisationer och myndigheter har stärkt kompetens att kunna att arbeta och implementera immaterialrätts-system i enlighet med nationella prioriteringar och utvecklingsmålen. 3. PRV upprättar ömsesidigt och hållbart samarbete med olika nya aktörer som ytterligare kan stärka institutionaliseringen av kapacitetsutvecklingen inom området immaterialrätt i de minst utvecklade länderna (MUL). 4. Nationell och internationell samverkan mellan immaterialrättskontor och brottsbekämpande organ inrättas.

description.narrative: Covid pandemin innebar en förvandling av fysiska aktiviteter till digitala där PRV har hittat tekniska lösningar men också ser behov att vidare utveckla och också användning av digitala verktyg för deltagarna. Teresa Soops och Michelle Bouchard medverkade i ett video som sändes under Intellectual Property Day i april 2021, och där de beskrev samarbete mellan PRV, Sidas forskningssamarbete (enhet FORSK) och forskningsinstitut i Bangladesh, International Center for Diarrheal Diseases, ICDDR,B som har varit instrumentalt i framtagande av kolera vaccinet, ORS (Oral rehydration solution) forskning som stals och patenterades av Gatorade, och Pumpy'Nut som är en behandling för akuta undernärings fall som också stals och patenterades av ett fransk företag och som nu säljs till bl.a. WFP och UNHCR för undernärda barn. Resultat under 2020 är att ICDDR,B har sökt om två patent och nu har möjlighet att skydda sin forskning. Exempel på landnivå: Nepal: Subash Ghimire’s project on building IPR capacity at Kathmandu University in Nepal. Mr Ghimire’s work included network building with ITP alumni at Kathmandu University, giving presentations on IPR to students at Kathmandu University as well as at University of Salzburg in Austria, and at an international workshop. The project also included course curriculum development for including IPR as a segment in mandatory courses as well as developing an elective course entirely dedicated to IPR. The alumni network at Kathmandu University together with the course curriculum development provide good conditions for a sustained IPR capacity building at Kathmandu University and in Nepal. Myanmar: Thazin Han’s project on raising awareness about the process of technology transfer to different stakeholders in the public and private sectors in Myanmar. Myanmar was formulating a national science, technology, and innovation (STI) policy, prior to the military take-over and one of the aims of Ms Han’s project was to create awareness on the importance of including technology transfer, IPR and patent information in the national STI policy. Among the activities organized within the project were five roundtable discussions involving different stakeholders. In total, these discussions on IP matters, including defining needs and challenges for each sector, reached to almost 200 attendees. The project also comprised creating awareness at the highest political level where Ms Thun had the chance to reach out to the Vice President of Myanmar, after which the Vice President included the importance of IPR in a speech circulated to all STI related ministries and to the public in Myanmar. The project may continue in collaboration with WIPO, when circumstances within the country improves. Tanzania: Robertson Michael Simbagije’s project aims at transforming agriculture through breeding modernization, plant protection and commercialization for sustainable development. The project included awareness creation and capacity building by participation in meetings, farmers field days, expositions, and conferences. Furthermore, an IP related institution was established, the BREEDERS’ INNOVATORS’ AND INVENTORS’ SOCIETY OF TANZANIA (BIIST). The objectives of BIIST include to protect the interests of plant breeders including intellectual property rights, to negotiate on behalf and for the interest of all breeders, inventors, and innovators, to promote conservation and sustainable utilization of plant genetic resources, to promote commercialization of breeder seeds, certified seeds, and all seed grades and to establish data bases for breeding technical information and genetic conservation in Tanzania. The organization will be working for plant breeder’s rights in collaboration with national and international organizations. Uganda: Mr. Kafunjo from the “Uganda Registration Services Bureau” made a review of the legal and policy framework on intellectual property and genetic resources and traditional knowledge (TK). The aim was to raise awareness among a multitude of strategic stakeholders, both from the private and public sector, to examine current practices and experiences, and to make suggestions on how to improve the legal system in relation to Intellectual Property, Traditional Knowledge and Genetic Resources. During his review, he gathered policies and legal framework in the different IP areas, as well as suggested ways to strengthen sensitization, adaptation of the law into local dialects, thus facilitating awareness- raising to benefit all the communities; ratifying some acts, implementation of different policies content in the legal framework; just to mention some of those suggestions. The participant concluded that the review in the project gave him the opportunity to identify several areas that need harmonization, improvement and collaboration and the work done can help various stakeholders to benefit other stakeholders, such as innovators, researchers and academia and traditional medicine practitioners to make sustainable use of genetic resources an TK for sustainable socioeconomic and the intellectual property development. Kenya: The project “Biotechnology Intellectual Property Management Manual” from a participant from the National Biosafety Authority. The project compiled different activities that lead to the development of a draft guide on IP in biotechnology industry to assist decision making for commercialisation and avoid infringement of IP-rights. The project is timely as biotech is growing fast in Kenya, while the return on investment is slow. The manual provides a summary of aspects of the IP management process from conception of an idea through to its protection and subsequent successful commercialisation and in addition to the resources used in conjunction with the existing IP management policies and practices of research institutions, companies, and research funders and to fill the gap by assisting all sectors to effectively and efficiently manage this most important resource and to maximise its potential benefits to society.
